{"questionId":"26045","questionHtml":"<p>Use linear regression to estimate the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp;and of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>Q</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow><mi>Q</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>42228</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5561</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mi>Q</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><br>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong> </em>for each coefficient seen – not necessarily in the equation. Do not penalize seeing in the context of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>.</p>\n<p><br>identifying that the constant is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math> <strong>OR</strong> that the gradient is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>k</mi><mi>L</mi></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>therefore&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>422</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>422228</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>k</mi><mi>L</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5561</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>165000</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mn>165205</mn></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><br>Note:</strong> Accept a value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>164843</mn></math> from use of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> sf value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>, or any other value from plausible pre-rounding.<br>Allow follow-through <strong>within</strong> the question part, from the equation of their line to the final two <em><strong>A1</strong></em> marks.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"26045","referenceCode":"22M.3.AHL.TZ1.1f.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Use linear regression to estimate the value of k and of L.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"f.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}